steps.text:
Yes—this is supported now. `useThemeProps` is public and documented for custom, themeable components:

```tsx
import { styled, useThemeProps } from '@mui/material/styles';

const MyCustomComponentRoot = styled('div', {
  name: 'MuiMyCustomComponent',
  slot: 'root',
})(({ theme }) => ({
  padding: theme.spacing(2),
}));

export function MyCustomComponent(inProps) {
  const props = useThemeProps({
    props: inProps,
    name: 'MuiMyCustomComponent',
  });

  return <MyCustomComponentRoot {...props} />;
}
```

Use the same component name in the theme:

```tsx
const theme = createTheme({
  components: {
    MuiMyCustomComponent: {
      defaultProps: {
        variant: 'dashed',
      },
      styleOverrides: {
        root: {
          variants: [
            {
              props: { variant: 'dashed' },
              style: { border: '2px dashed' },
            },
          ],
        },
      },
    },
  },
});
```

For full support, define slots through `styled()` with the component `name` and `slot`, pass an `ownerState` object when styles depend on props, and add TypeScript module augmentation if applicable.

Material UI now has a dedicated guide and template for this exact use case: [Creating themed components](https://mui.com/material-ui/customization/creating-themed-components/).
